Extended Unix Code for Japanese (EUC-JP) CP20932 Encoding and Decoding

Published July 30, 2024
By Samuel Yang

CP20932 is the code page identifier for the EUC-JP (Extended Unix Code for Japanese) encoding, which is used for representing Japanese text on computers. EUC-JP is one of several encodings used for Japanese text, and it allows for the representation of a wide range of characters from the Japanese writing system, including kanji, hiragana, katakana, and Latin characters.

EUC-JP stands for Extended Unix Code for Japanese. It is designed to encode a mix of ASCII, Kana, and Kanji characters efficiently. The encoding supports the following character sets:

  • ASCII: Standard Latin characters, digits, punctuation, and control characters.
  • JIS X 0208: A character set for Kanji and other Japanese characters, encoded in two-byte sequences.
  • JIS X 0201: A set that includes half-width Katakana.
  • JIS X 0212: A supplementary set of Kanji characters, encoded using three-byte sequences in EUC-JP.

EUC-JP uses different byte sequences to represent different types of characters:

  • ASCII Characters: 1 byte, using the same range as standard ASCII (0x00-0x7F).
  • JIS X 0201 (Half-Width Katakana): Encoded with two bytes, where the first byte is 0x8E (known as "SS2") and the second byte is in the range 0xA1-0xDF.
  • JIS X 0208 (Kanji): Encoded with two bytes, both in the range 0xA1-0xFE.
  • JIS X 0212 (Additional Kanji Characters): Encoded with three bytes, where the first byte is 0x8F (known as "SS3") and the subsequent two bytes are in the range 0xA1-0xFE.

Two-Byte Characters (JIS X 0208)

JIS X 0208 is a widely used character set standard for Japanese that includes Kanji, Hiragana, Katakana, and various other symbols. In EUC-JP encoding, characters from the JIS X 0208 set are encoded using two-byte sequences.

The EUC-JP code table is organized into sections to categorize different sets of characters. In EUC-JP, characters are often represented in a two-byte sequence where the first byte indicates the section and the second byte indicates the position within that section.

Section 01 characters include punctuation marks, symbols, and other commonly used characters.
